@sliceofNai They should know better! My managers used to press at the beginning of the remote stage about having cameras on, but I think they eventually realized that aside from appearance, some people were just struggling and didn't want to be seen.
@stomptheyarnpdx I love that. Working remotely gave me a lot of freedom and courage to do what I please with my appearance and hair. I'm glad I'm not alone in that.

I think a lot of people just do not realize that it takes us a lot of effort to present in person and on camera, especially in a pandemic when many really struggled to do the most basic of tasks. There’s no getting out of bed and “fluffing” my hair to be ready for me.

I cannot tell you how many times in the last two years that I’ve sat in meetings w/ the camera off because I didn’t feel like doing my hair or taking off my scarf/bonnet for that day. And didn’t care if anyone challenged that I didn’t feel like turning on my cam for the day.

One day, we’ll have a discussion about how the drastic switch to remote work due to the pandemic positively impacted professional Black women because of the lack of pressure to always have our hair “ready” and “faces” on to engage in the workplace.

Unless that’s just me.

Bottom line: 

• We sometimes hear what we want to hear in people’s words instead of taking their words at face value. 
• Stop projecting your own thoughts, insecurities, and biases onto others. 
• Words don’t have to be hard and they do mean things. 
• Be a better listener.

Example: one of our paralegals was asked about a new workload manager. She clearly stated her concern and the managing attorneys responded by addressing something totally out of the scope of what she said. It was weird to me b/c I thought that what she was saying was clear. Lol.

People misunderstand and incorrectly read into what someone else has (clearly) stated so often that it’s scary. It’s like we ignore the clear meaning of what was said and apply our own biases to it, causing unnecessary misunderstanding, dialogue, and confusion.
